Steady-state kinetics of Fe/N@ C-dots were investigated via recording the absorbance at 652 nm for 20 min (Fig. 7
                         A&B). Moreover, the values of Vmax and Km were calculated from Lineweaver-Burk plot (Fig. 7C&D). Kinetic parameters of Fe/N@ C-dots were compared with horseradish peroxidase (HRP) and other nanozymes (Table 2
                        ). It is clearly seen that the as-fabricated Fe/N@ C-dots have low Km and higher Vmax values, suggesting the ability of Fe/N@ C-dots to catalyze substrate more rapidly than other nanozymes and HRP. These results indicated that Fe/N@ C-dots could be an alternative to HRP and used for rapid H2O2 and glucose determination.
